\f0\fs26 \cf0 Newton first law of motion states that once an object is in motion, it tends to remain in motion unless it is acted upon by an outside force. This theory fits well with what Buffett calls \'93the institutional imperative.\'94 By this he means that once a course of action has been decided, it is very difficult to fight inertia and get off that track. For example, if a firm\'92s CEO decides that the company should make an acquisition and has expressed a high level of interest in one company in particular, you can almost bet his subordinates will produce numbers supporting his theory on why that company should be purchased. Something akin to this also occurs when one firm in an industry purchases a company of a certain type, and then other firms scramble to purchase similar companies.\
\'93For every action there is an equal and opposite reaction\'94 nicely sums up Newton\'92s third law of motion. This ties in well with understand the market, as it is a complex system and reacts to stimuli in the same manner. For instance, when a financial crisis occurs, many individuals will panic and submit sell orders to their brokers, causing stocks to fall to a point where other investors will step in to purchase a now undervalued security.\
