The fourth law is evident in a study conducted by Brian Bushee, a professor at Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania. He split the institutional investing community into three classifications: transient, dedicated and quasi-indexers. Bushee found that 31% of institutional shareholders were \'93transient investors,\'94 8% were \'93dedicated\'94 investors and 61% were \'93quasi-indexers.\'94\
\'93Transient\'94 institutional investors hold well-diversified portfolios of publicly traded securities; they pursue short-term profits through high turnover of their portfolios and heavy use of momentum trading.\
\'93Dedicated\'94 institutional investors have substantial investments in a relatively small number of portfolio companies; they hold a high percentage (often more than 75%) of their portfolio shares for two years or more.\
\'93Quasi-indexers\'94 fall between the two other categories of institutional investors; they have highly diversified portfolios of publicly traded securities and also a high degree of ownership continuity since they seldom trade.\
